  "topic_name": "Light",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Light is a form of energy that enables us to see objects. Objects that produce their own light are called luminous objects (like the Sun and bulbs), while objects that do not produce light are non-luminous objects. Light travels in straight lines. Based on how much light passes through, materials are classified as transparent (allows all light), translucent (allows some light), or opaque (blocks all light). Shadows are formed when light is blocked by opaque objects. Reflection is the bouncing back of light from a surface. Plane mirrors form images that are the same size, laterally inverted, and appear to be at the same distance behind the mirror.",
    "rules": [
      "Light is a form of energy that helps us see.",
      "Luminous objects produce their own light.",
      "Non-luminous objects do not produce light.",
      "Light travels in straight lines (rectilinear propagation).",
      "Transparent objects allow light to pass through completely.",
      "Translucent objects allow some light to pass through.",
      "Opaque objects do not allow light to pass through.",
      "Shadows are formed when opaque objects block light.",
      "Reflection is the bouncing back of light from a surface.",
      "Plane mirrors form virtual, erect, same-size, and laterally inverted images."
    ]
  },
